The printStackTrace method is said to print the stack trace for the exception *and* any exception(s) embedded in the status. But, populating a CoreException with a status holding a 'cause', it only seems to print the stacktrace for the cause - the stacktrace for the CoreException itself is lost! A sample program attached below, gives me the result:

org.eclipse.core.runtime.CoreException: error
	at Main.main(Main.java:15)
======
org.eclipse.core.runtime.CoreException[0]: java.lang.Exception: cause
	at Main.throwCause(Main.java:41)
	at Main.main(Main.java:26)

I.e. first a test with no 'cause' (looks as expected), and then wrapping a 'cause' (only prints the cause, but I'd expected it also to print that the CoreException itself happened (at line 30, in my case).

public class Main
{
	public static void main(String[] args)
	{
		try
		{
			throw new CoreException(new Status(IStatus.ERROR, "test", 0, "error", null));
		}
		catch(Exception e)
		{
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
		System.out.println("======");
		try
		{
			try
			{
				throwCause();
			}
			catch(Exception e)
			{
				throw new CoreException(new Status(IStatus.ERROR, "test", 0, "error", e));
			}
		}
		catch(Exception e)
		{
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}

	private static void throwCause() throws Exception
	{
		throw new Exception("cause");
	}
}
